s discourses of digression, dissent, and the transcendence of the commonplace. Who could even imagine modern writing without the addictive, visionary excesses of writers like Baudelaire, DeQuincey, Poe, Burroughs, or Artaud? Or, for that matter, modern culture without its "outsiders," its incorrigible addicts, its defaced subjects: smokers, users, overeaters, alcoholics, the insane? Taking a cultural studies approach to addiction, High Culture offers a readable and accessible collection of essays on these socially marginalized practices and discourses so central to modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCivilization, Modern. 0aCreative ability. 0aInspiration. 0aSubstance abuse. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / History.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAllison, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClej, Alina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerrida, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElster, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzgerald, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreaves, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuattari, Félix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsrael, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLingis, Alphonso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLothane, Zvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul